[src:1886-baltimore-orioles-season/1882-baltimore-orioles-season] The 19th century's version of the **Baltimore Orioles** were founded in 1882 as part of the new American Association.
[src:1886-baltimore-orioles-season/1882-baltimore-orioles-season] Owned by wealthy Harry Von der Horst, the Orioles finished the season in last place with only 19 wins.
[src:1886-baltimore-orioles-season/1886-boston-beaneaters-season] The **1886 Boston Beaneaters season** was the 16th season of the franchise.
[src:1886-baltimore-orioles-season/1886-brooklyn-grays-season] The **1886 Brooklyn Grays season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1886-baltimore-orioles-season/1886-brooklyn-grays-season] The team finished the season in third place with a record of 76–61 (their first winning season), 16 games behind the St.
[src:1886-baltimore-orioles-season/1886-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1886 Chicago White Stockings season** was the 15th season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the 11th in the National League and the second at the first West Side Park.
[src:1886-baltimore-orioles-season/1886-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings finished first in the National League with a record of 90–34, 2.5 games ahead of the second place Detroit Wolverines.
[src:1886-baltimore-orioles-season/1886-chicago-white-stockings-season] The team was defeated four games to two by the St.
[src:1886-baltimore-orioles-season/1886-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings lost the 1886 World Series to the St.
